# ğŸ“˜ WEEK 4 REPORT

## Month 1 â€“ Data Visualization with Matplotlib and Seaborn




# 1ï¸âƒ£ Objective

The objective of Week 4 was to understand data visualization techniques using Matplotlib and Seaborn to analyze relationships between dataset features.

---

# 2ï¸âƒ£ Concepts Learned

---

## ğŸ”¹ 1. Matplotlib

Matplotlib is a Python library used for creating basic plots and charts.

It is mainly used for:

* Line Charts
* Bar Charts
* Histograms
* Scatter Plots

---

### ğŸ“Š Common Matplotlib Plots

![Image](https://www.w3schools.com/python/img_matplotlib_line_red.png)

![Image](https://www.w3schools.com/python/img_matplotlib_bars1.png)

![Image](https://www.w3schools.com/python/img_matplotlib_histogram1.png)

![Image](https://files.realpython.com/media/commute_times.621e5b1ce062.png)

Example:

```python
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x = [1,2,3,4]
y = [10,20,25,30]

plt.plot(x,y)
plt.title("Line Chart")
plt.xlabel("X Axis")
plt.ylabel("Y Axis")
plt.show()
```

---

## ğŸ”¹ 2. Seaborn

Seaborn is built on top of Matplotlib and provides advanced statistical visualizations.

It is mainly used for:

* Heatmaps
* Pairplots
* Boxplots
* Distribution plots

---

### ğŸ“Š Common Seaborn Plots

![Image](https://seaborn.pydata.org/_images/heatmap_5_0.png)

![Image](https://seaborn.pydata.org/_images/pairplot_11_0.png)

![Image](https://seaborn.pydata.org/_images/boxplot_5_0.png)

![Image](https://seaborn.pydata.org/_images/boxplot_3_0.png)

Example:

```python
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

tips = sns.load_dataset("tips")
sns.scatterplot(x="total_bill", y="tip", data=tips)
plt.show()
```

